  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The frequency of Barrett's esophagus (BE) has increased in adults in the last decades, but BE
      is rare in children. Esophageal atresia (EA), the most common congenital anomaly affecting
      the esophagus, predisposes the patient to severe and prolonged gastroesophageal reflux
      disease. Because gastroesophageal reflux disease plays a major role in the development of BE
      by causing repeated mucosal damage, development of BE is a concern even in children and young
      adults in this specific population. The aim of this study is to assess the prevalence of BE
      (gastric and/or intestinal metaplasia) in a population of adolescents/young adults who had
      been treated for EA in early infancy. All eligible patients received upper gastrointestinal
      endoscopy under general anesthesia with standardized esophageal staged biopsies. Histological
      suspicion of metaplasia was confirmed centrally.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
